import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import networkx as nx

Read the graph

In [2]:
G= nx.read_edgelist("data/lesmis.txt", create_using=nx.DiGraph, nodetype=int, data=(('weight',float),)) # Read the network

#Edges larger than 5 are drawn as green lines; edges equal or smaller than 5 are blue lines
elarge = [(u, v) for (u, v, d) in G.edges(data=True) if d['weight'] > 5]
esmall = [(u, v) for (u, v, d) in G.edges(data=True) if d['weight'] <= 5]

Plot the weighted and directed Les Miserables graph

In [3]:
plt.figure(figsize=(25,25))
pos=nx.spring_layout(G)
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos, node_size=300)
nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos, edgelist=elarge,width=2, edge_color='g')
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos, edgelist=esmall,width=2, alpha=0.8, edge_color='b')

plt.show(block = False)
plt.clf()

Converting the graph to its undirected and unweighted version

In [4]:
G = G.to_undirected()
order = G.order()

for u in range(order):
    for v in range(order):
        if G.has_edge(u, v):
            G[u][v]['weight'] = 1

#Edges larger than 5 are drawn as black lines; edges equal or smaller than 5 are blue dashed lines
elarge = [(u, v) for (u, v, d) in G.edges(data=True) if d['weight'] > 5]
esmall = [(u, v) for (u, v, d) in G.edges(data=True) if d['weight'] <= 5]

Plot the unweighted and undirected Les Miserables graph (this isn't the optimal way to do it, but we did it to show that the results from this graph and the previous one are different even if we use the same code)

In [5]:
plt.figure(figsize=(25,25))
pos=nx.spring_layout(G)
nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G, pos, node_size=300)
nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos, edgelist=elarge,width=2)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos, edgelist=esmall,width=2, alpha=0.8, edge_color='b', style='dashed')

plt.show(block = False)
plt.clf()
